  <h2>1. Nature of Private Residential Tenancy</h2>
  <p>
    A Private Residential Tenancy (PRT) in Scotland is open-ended - it has no fixed term or end date. The
    tenancy continues until the tenant gives notice to leave, or the landlord successfully applies to the
    First-tier Tribunal for an eviction order based on one of the 18 grounds for eviction.
  </p>

  <h2>2. Rent</h2>
  <p>
    The Tenant agrees to pay the Rent on the days and in the manner specified in this Agreement.
  </p>
  <p>
    Rent is payable in advance. The Landlord may only increase the rent once in any 12-month period by
    following the statutory procedure set out in the Private Housing (Tenancies) (Scotland) Act 2016.
    The Tenant has the right to refer a proposed rent increase to a Rent Officer for adjudication.
  </p>
