  <h2>4. Statutory Terms</h2>
  <p>
    The Private Housing (Tenancies) (Scotland) Act 2016 includes mandatory statutory terms that automatically
    apply to all PRTs. These include:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>The tenant must notify the landlord of any defect or disrepair</li>
    <li>The tenant must not use the property for illegal purposes</li>
    <li>The tenant must not act in an antisocial manner</li>
    <li>The landlord must provide a tenancy agreement in writing</li>
    <li>The landlord must give proper notice before entry (except emergencies)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>5. Condition of Property - Repairing Standard</h2>
  <p>
    The Landlord must ensure the property meets the Repairing Standard and must:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Ensure the property is wind and watertight and reasonably fit for human habitation</li>
    <li>Keep in repair the structure and exterior (including drains, gutters, external pipes)</li>
    <li>Keep in repair and working order the installations for water, gas, electricity, heating, and hot water</li>
    <li>Keep in repair and working order sanitary installations (baths, sinks, toilets)</li>
    <li>Ensure the property has satisfactory fire detection and carbon monoxide detection</li>
    <li>Provide a valid electrical safety inspection (EICR) every 5 years</li>
    <li>Provide a valid Gas Safety Certificate annually (if the property has gas)</li>
    <li>Provide a valid Energy Performance Certificate (EPC)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    <strong>Note:</strong> Tenants can apply to the First-tier Tribunal if the landlord fails to meet
    the Repairing Standard.
  </p>

  <h2>6. Tenant's Obligations</h2>
  <p>
    The Tenant agrees to:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Keep the property clean and in good condition</li>
    <li>Promptly report any defects or disrepair to the Landlord</li>
    <li>Not damage or alter the property without written consent</li>
    <li>Not use the property for any illegal purpose</li>
    <li>Not behave in an antisocial manner</li>
    <li>Return the property in the same condition at the end of the tenancy (fair wear and tear excepted)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>7. Access for Repairs</h2>
  <p>
    The Tenant must allow the Landlord reasonable access to inspect the property and carry out repairs,
    subject to giving at least 48 hours' written notice (except in emergencies). The landlord must give
    reasonable notice before any inspection or visit.
  </p>

  <h2>8. Subletting and Assignment</h2>
  <p>
    The Tenant must not:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Sublet the whole or part of the property</li>
    <li>Assign or transfer the tenancy</li>
    <li>Take in lodgers</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Without the Landlord's prior written consent.</p>

  <h2>9. Ending the Tenancy</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Tenant's Notice:</strong> The Tenant may end the tenancy at any time by giving the Landlord
    at least 28 days' written notice.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Landlord's Notice:</strong> The Landlord may only end the tenancy by serving a Notice to Leave
    based on one of the 18 statutory grounds for eviction and, if the tenant does not leave, by obtaining
    an eviction order from the First-tier Tribunal for Scotland (Housing and Property Chamber).
  </p>
  <p>
    The notice period depends on the ground for eviction:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>28 days:</strong> Grounds 1-8, 12-16 (if tenancy less than 6 months)</li>
    <li><strong>84 days:</strong> Grounds 1-8, 12-16 (if tenancy 6 months or more)</li>
    <li><strong>Immediate or shorter:</strong> Grounds 9-11 (serious grounds such as criminal behaviour)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>10. Tenant's Right to Quiet Enjoyment</h2>
  <p>
    The Tenant has the right to "quiet enjoyment" of the property. The Landlord must not interfere with
    the Tenant's use and enjoyment of the property without lawful excuse.
  </p>

  <h2>11. Landlord Registration</h2>
  <p>
    All private landlords in Scotland must be registered with their local authority. It is a criminal
    offence to let property in Scotland without being registered. You can check landlord registration
    at <a href="https://www.landlordregistrationscotland.gov.uk">landlordregistrationscotland.gov.uk</a>.
  </p>

